  "prompt": "How is WhatsApp able to show the blurred image even after deleting the original copy from the gallery?",
  "response": "When you see a blurred version of an image on WhatsApp despite having deleted the original copy from your gallery, it is likely because WhatsApp keeps a low-resolution thumbnail of the image within its local database or cache for the app. Here\u2019s how this generally works:\n\n1. **Thumbnails:** When images are sent or received on WhatsApp, the app generates a smaller, lower-resolution version of the image, known as a thumbnail. This is typically stored separately from the original high-resolution image to be used in the chat interface for quicker load times and reduced data usage.\n\n2. **Local Storage and Cache:** These thumbnails can be stored in the app\u2019s cached data, allowing the app to load images quickly without needing the original file. This cache or database often persists even when files are deleted from the device\u2019s gallery, allowing for the display of a blurred or low-quality version of the image in chat.\n\n3. **Chats Synchronization:** WhatsApp may also continue to show information from its own database if the chat is backed up or if the conversation view has been cached within the app, independent of the device's local storage.\n\n4. **Retention of Metadata:** WhatsApp might retain some metadata or reference information about the deleted images for continuity within chats. Because of this, the chat application can present a placeholder or blurred version of the image even if the high-resolution file is no longer available on your device.\n\nThis system is designed to optimize load times and reduce network usage, and typically these thumbnails or cached images take up significantly less space on your device compared to the original files.",
